							　　The foundation offered to help Beike set up a clinical-trial protocol that would include creating a registry of patient outcomes. Joseph Cosico, the foundation’s vice-president for research operations, says that Beike declined the offer "because of their inability to fund the venture". Beike says that it decided to work with another group, partly for cost reasons, but would not provide any details of that collaboration.　　　　"I can understand why they wouldn’t want to do a trial," says cell biologist Duanqing Pei, director-general of the Guangzhou Institute of Biomedicine and Health. "They might spend millions of dollars to prove that the treatment isn’t effective."　　
							
							
						

